The devices to track people are increasingly being asked by parents who want to watch their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think about watching them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can be used just as well to trace the movement of people and help in some cases, such as that of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a box of matches but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka has moved many people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not about espionage, but only about another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracing devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
"Most people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons," said Pilin.
According to him, children should always know what "box" is used for and how to use it in an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to wear something like this on him, he will get rid of it.
'And even the little ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something on purpose when they don't want to be under control.'
" Cell phones, which can be cut like these tracking devices, have already led parents to long expectations," says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is highly questionable.
"If this is a prepared abduction, the author will do everything to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate it."
"Currently, it's the phone."
"As soon as tracing devices develop, they (criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
She admits, however, that such devices can help during an attack not prepared by a paedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, who offers tracking services for both cars and people, he claims that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an attack.
"The device can be set in such a way that it is on a regular broadcast after a specified period."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains."
'The most expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and finds himself in a lying position without moving," says Cech.
According to him the so-called smart mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formatted it with a special prologiciel.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to those worn as a pendant of the size of a box of matches or to the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the company Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the possible attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he'll find out after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as for tracing cars.
This is a combination of a GPS position acquisition system (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
