A longer index than the annular is a sign of low cancer risk
Men with a longer index than the annular are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple risk test for prostate cancer, especially for men before 60 years of age," said co-author Ros Eeles, professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
The finger could help determine which men should undergo the prostate cancer test, including by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, said Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index of the right hand shorter than the annular.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had the same length of fingers, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
For those with a longer index than the yearbook, however, the risk has fallen to 33 percent, for men before 60 years the decrease in risk has reached 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two fingers cited - formed during the prenatal period - indicates, among other things, different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it was testosterone that helped develop prostate cancer.
Prof. Vacla Pates, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of this study but that it does not seem to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
