Prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
The prosecutors of the Department of Justice raised the criminal charges against Senator John Ensign arising from a case involving an assistant from an old campaign and his efforts to obtain lobbying work for the wife's husband, announced on Wednesday the honourable senator's lawyers.
The decision put an end to the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Republican of Nevada, who was considered a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election until the scandal surrounding his case became the major national headlines last year and adversely affected his career.
Mr. Ensign's office stated that he was "very happy" with the decision, the result of a year-long investigation.
The honourable senator could still be exposed to disciplinary action taken by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers stated that the Department of Justice had "reported that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the investigation and that he did not intend to hold any charges against him in this matter."
The Department of Justice has refrained from commenting on this matter.
The announcement came as a sort of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice that there would be significant evidence that Mr. Ensign would have conspired to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get a lucrative lobbying job to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the honourable senator's affair with her.
Ms. Hampton once served as treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited for a year by law from lobbying with his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethical experts argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appears to be in contradiction with the so-called ban on the rotating door of lobbying.
According to evidence made public, "there seems to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and violate the law of the revolving door," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients from an investigation by the government.
Although the department's judge refused to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in Ensign, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department seemed to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of high-level setbacks by its public integrity section, including last year's decisions to abandon prosecutions against former Senator Ted Stevens accused of misconduct.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take the weapons," said Melanie Sloan, the Director General of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defence group that received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government official can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Senior Counsel for Mr.Ensign, stated in an interview that he had received a telephone call from a prosecutor from the Department of Justice on Monday and a follow-up the next day, telling him that the department was not looking for charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's team of lawyers had cooperated with the prosecutors to try to persuade them that the honourable senator, as his office reaffirmed on Wednesday in a statement, "had acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments he had made at the prosecutor's office.
"I'm not comfortable getting into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to abandon an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that the payment of $96,000 by Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal electoral law.
The Electoral Commission stated that it did not have sufficient evidence to prove that the money was everything but a gift.
NV Energy, an important Nevada corporation that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An e-mail sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he "martelized" the Ministry of the Interior on a matter in dispute.
Mr. Ensign also attended a luncheon with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and asked the Transport Secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after hiring Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When the news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign stated two weeks ago that he intended to fight for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, said that the honourable senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and put an end to his investigation.
Senator Ensign is pleased to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she said.
