Can civilization bring the divides closer together?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civilization broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a warning sign of genuine bipartite cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the early return to partisan struggle in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and Congressional leaders has produced no breakthroughs on the major issues that need to be addressed during the "bottle duck" session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each camp wanted to score points.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the committee on the President's deficit was equally civilised, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide, but which, however, still divides the members.
It is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both sides are now in a period of trial and mutual testing with a view to obtaining signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That is why the Tuesday meeting and the subsequent comments of the participants revealed a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and too profound to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
In terms of taxation, spending, health care or rights, both parties remain miles away.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed in tone," said Pete Wehner, an official of the Bush administration, now next to the Centre for Ethics and Public Policy.
"It's inevitable after the election.
The elections stir up partisan passions and then they fail.
That's good."
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the "bottle duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve a part or the whole of it, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, perhaps only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, while refusing unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After the meeting on Tuesday at the White House, more optimism is based on a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on "boitous duck", with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing problems of the "lame duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better agreement between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
"Once the things that have to be done will be done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civilization would lead to true cooperation.
"I consider most of what is going on between today and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow boxing compared to the 2012 main event," he said.
The reasons for this are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and to the tea voters who contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to live up to their promises to reduce public spending and repeal the new Health Care Act.
These partisan positions are already clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the deficit committee, which include reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, raising retirement age and reducing expenditure.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, in their view, imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the committee, composed of 18 members, to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have had difficulty reaching that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected representatives, suggesting that there is little reason or willingness to compromise on tax issues, at least today.
Galston foresees two phases in the fights between the White House and the Republicans of Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan confrontations, as Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care; and then be followed by a period of greater bipartite cooperation.
What would be the cause of change?
Public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see both parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the public.
Those who will be judged to be in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would be an optimistic point of view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are bigger today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans of Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, the activists of both parties saw 2010 as a simple prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But much more effort will be needed on both sides to find a common ground on the issues that still divide them.
