Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face the past
In a poorly lit classroom with decrepit concrete walls of poor quality, the director of the secondary school of Anlong Veng mentioned the man who had built it, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here likes Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader; and he cared about his people," said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, when he was at the head of the Khmer Rouge, this commander remains popular in this isolated bastion of former Khmer Rouge in northwestern Cambodia where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge went to the government, long-standing loyalty is finally challenged at Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to face publicly the people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school manual that, for the first time, teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And, in July, a Cambodian court, jointly led by the United Nations, handed down its first sentence concerning a former Khmer Rouge member, condemning, to 35 years in prison, the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture centre, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as "Duch".
Faced with this evolution of the situation, anxiety has increased among the veterans of the Khmer Rouge of Anlong Veng; complicating reconciliation efforts and their willingness to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There are resentments and fear among the old Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Centre, an independent organization that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the diet became a symbol of evil."
"The situation generates divisions within families."
During the reign of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overcrowding.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overturned the Pol Pot U.S. government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There, they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last of the movements went in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary were leading the guerrillas at their base in the mountains of western Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a suite at Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a peace agreement sponsored by the United Nations led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to defuse the government, culminating in the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 pending trial.
Without their benefactors, most Khmer Rouge veterans have plunged into black poverty, common to the rural regions of Cambodia; and many remain nostalgic of the movement.
Although some Khmer Rouge elite officers have retained their positions as local leaders in exchange for having laid down the weapons, they are low-grade, unskilled farmers.
"These people received very little follow-up after capitulation," said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are imbued with the agrarian utopian ideology of the regime."
"They were raised in a context where doing business is a foreign concept."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as a poor rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Your Mok feeds everyone."
But now life is difficult because we have to support our own needs."
The Khmer Rouge Court in progress has also caused concerns here.
At the beginning of next year, the court should begin the judgment of Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Red Minister.
The court's mandate is to try the senior leaders and the principal perpetrators of the crimes, but he did not say whether he continued beyond these four cases.
It would take more to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
The latest media speculations were directed towards 64-year-old Im Chaem, a former district chief in the province of Banteay Meanchey under the reign of the Khmer Rouge in the 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Centre that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project where thousands of forced workers would have died.
Recently, during a torrid evening, Im Chaem returned from work to the field near his wooden house on pilotis, on a dirt road outside of Anlong Veng.
While the sun cast long shadows on the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past within the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she said, she would refuse to go.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable," she said.
"If there is more prosecution, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected the Khmer Rouge in 1978, also repeatedly warned that instability would occur if the court pursued several suspects; although experts and historians contested this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But facing the past is all Cambodia has to do to move forward, says Youk Chhang, from the documentation centre.
"Reconciliation in Khmer terms is to reconnect broken pieces," he says.
"We have to put these pieces together so we can understand."
The centre produced the first government-approved manual on the Khmer Rouge, "A History of Democratic Kampuchea, composed of 75 pages."
He distributed it in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the history manuals of the Ministry of Education, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know only a few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new manual helped students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted skeptically when he came back with the book at home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the manual and the court," he says.
"They do not trust because they do not know exactly how many people the court will continue."
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, the manual and the court are beginning to have an impact, he said.
Yet, the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful attraction here.
