Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee sanctioned with two games the coach of the team, José Mourinho and various economic sums to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances such as this or similar is not a new practice, if not more frequent in the football world.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, unwritten but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the debate that appeared in the case related is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the entity of Real Madrid (who in his anthem displays nobility and honor and who on past occasions has sentenced to a fine to his players for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, which adds one more episode to his dilated history of hystrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour does not expressly prohibit by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is to say, whether with these actions we commit a fraud of law; because, in fact, they are actions respectful of the sports regulation, but seem to elude its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that understands the sports spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been put in jeopardy, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with the right game is to prevent the team of infringing players from benefiting unfairly from the opposite team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not conform to what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in hiding to try to avoid punishment, but their action has precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the arbitrator.
They were waiting and they willingly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of advantage that offenders gain from intentional misconduct.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put in a situation of disadvantage to the rival and one does not get an advantage in the same game either, because obviously the result of the action presupposes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn't count on these players.
Of course, the advantage is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term advantage, with some degree of indeterminateness, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from this, with this action the players perform a penalty game and move to the second cycle of cartons, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cartons occurs with one less than the first cycle.
So, climbing the steps, it's not so clear that this is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to the sporting spirit, which is still part of strategic decision-making that promotes profit to the maximum of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the penalty (this would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law), otherwise they chose rather the time when they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without derailing the penalty or running away from it.
Even though the boundary between genius and lawlessness is widespread, on this occasion I think we've had a clear case of genius.
The controversy seems to me to be due to two factors: because there have been two self-expulsions and because of the way the Director transmits to provoke them.
The evil caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
