The European Union changes the rules for obtaining a visa
People need to go to Visa Applicant Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011 the visa processing procedure at the Embassy and Consulates of the United States will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will be required to appear at the Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASC) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have some advantages for applicants, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The seeker will make a single payment covering all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Those who wish to renew their visa will not have to present themselves to an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only present themselves to the nearest CSA where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken into the CSA, applicants who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain there less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra $26 fee.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletins/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
