A Global Plan to Refurbish Lighting
Yesterday in Cancún, the United Nations proposed a plan for the renovation of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries with a view to achieving a greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction that corresponds almost one third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in line with the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to have adopted in Cancun to offset the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to yesterday's plan, if incandescent bulbs that still monopolize from 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, better, by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), the bulk of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHGs emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of global fleet emissions.
Last year in Copenhagen, major emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should shift overall GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But we will have to subtract 5 Gt from this balance sheet in order to stabilize by 2020 the increase in climate to 2 degrees centigrade in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of energy dissipates in the form of heat and the remainder, or 5%, produces light.
With fluocompact bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this need for energy is reduced twice again.
Fluocompact bulbs last from an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, like those launched by Philips this week - this company has also participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These all new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emit very little heat.
And they contain no mercury.
Several specialists have posted reserves for fluocompact bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
But, the report says, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact bulb, but rather coal thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce waste electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost it 2.5 billion.
