Avenger hackers and spies in diligence
The WikiLeaks case has double value.
On the one hand, it proves to be an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears to be a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and prefigures a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file consisting of a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only bring back what could be read in any newspaper for months (except for those owned by Berlusconi), and Khadafi's sinisterly caricature profile was long-standing for Cabaret sketch artists.
The rule that secret records should only be composed of news already known is essential to the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookshop dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that every book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in previous books.
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (and does not know where to look for news about the inexistant), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism believe only that they already know, and that reconfirms what they had already learned.
It's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same for secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited in spirit) the head of the secret services (or else he could be, as I know, editor at Liberation), who only retain what he recognizes as true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
Then why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what any cultivated person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of state can telephone or fly a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representation exercises, have turned into spy centres.
Any viewer of investigative films knows that very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
So the scandal does not put both the victims and the "boars" in crisis.
But let's come to the deep nature of what happened.
Once, in Orwell's time, we could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had proved completely since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
The power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the revenger of the citizen - can know all the secrets of the power.
How can a power that no longer has the opportunity to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is true, too, that all knowing about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret of secrecy, because it falls within the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means removing all power from him.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but made it too big for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury to a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, the states will no longer be able to put on-line any reserved information - this would mean publishing it on a sticky poster on the corner of the street.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is hopeless to be able to maintain confidential reports over the telephone.
Nothing easier than finding out if and when a head of state moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my prediction is about science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligence to uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept in a single copy in locked drawers: in the background, the attempt to spy on the Watergate was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I have had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in crabs, that is to say, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wired telegraph (telephones).
Videocassettes (analogics) had allowed cinema researchers to explore a film step by step, going forward and back and discovering all the secrets of the editing, while now CDs (digital) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is not extraordinary that communications policy and techniques should return to horse-riding cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was going on in the secret of embassies.
Now it is the embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France pushes its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to review compliance with the rapidly unlocked funding promises (such fast start or early start funding) made by developed countries.
And the big French jams are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries committed themselves to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (or 420 million euros per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU launched the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, large side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation is appreciable and valued at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
In 2010, the EU announced EUR 2.2 billion, putting it on the right track to meet its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look at it in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must, according to the Copenhagen agreement, be "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States whose France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference year: international financing is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years to fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France believes that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or to the overall level of official development assistance.
Specifically, the total amount of France's support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and each chooses its method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that 1€ loaned is equivalent to 1€ given.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to emission mitigation that are based on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At the very least, it should be counted as part of its commitments only the cost of the loan to the lender country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing to do with such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of €420 million by making 91.5% of loans (€388.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (€36.1 million) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) fulfil their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1€ to satisfy its commitment, France only puts 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice lap pass!
In short, in its fast-start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, she is able to suggest that she spends €420 million "new and additional" in line with her promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely dupes...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, short-term issue compared to all climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge UNFCCC machine.
Let's hope that's not the case.
In any case, it is essential to draw lessons from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its method of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and equity with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently discussed): the issue of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans will not be avoided.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
Hope therefore rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about the fast start of France and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to advance in the discussions.
